<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1899-01-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1899-01-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="67" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d67">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Bridgman</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1899-01-24"><hi rend="italic">January 24,
                                1899</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 63.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            No. 73, of the 15th ultimo, reporting the outbreak of a revolution at La
                            Paz, and stating that it is probable you will be asked to shelter
                            refugees.</p>
                        <p>As to the question of shelter, as distinguished from so-called asylum,
                            you may consult the Deparment’s instruction to the minister of the
                            United States to Ecuador, printed in <ref target="frus1895p1#pg_215">Foreign Relations, 1895, page 215</ref>.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>